TY  - JOUR
AU  - Griffin, John M.
AU  - Xu, Jin
T1  - How Smart Are the Smart Guys? A Unique View from Hedge Fund Stock Holdings
PY  - 2009
Y1  - 2009/07/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhp026
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 22
IS  - 7
SP  - 2531
EP  - 2570
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - Compared to mutual funds, hedge funds prefer smaller, opaque value securities, and have higher turnover and more active share bets. Decomposing returns into three components, we find that hedge funds are better than mutual funds at stock picking by only 1.32% per year on a value-weighted basis, and this result is insignificant on an equal-weighted basis or with price-to-sales benchmarks. Hedge funds exhibit no ability to time sectors or pick better stock styles. Surprisingly, we find only weak evidence of differential ability between hedge funds. Overall, our study raises serious questions about the perceived superior skill of hedge fund managers.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhp026
ER  - 



